# Let us look at the target column which is 'salary' to understand how the data is distributed amongst the various values

adult_df['salary'] = adult_df['salary'].replace({' <=50K' : 'equal_to', ' <=50K.': 'equal_to', ' >50K': 'less_than', ' >50K.': 'less_than'})

# replacing wrongly written less than to greater than
adult_df['salary'] = adult_df['salary'].replace({'equal_to' : 'smaller_than' ,'less_than' : 'greater_than'})

# Most of them are having salary <= 50K. The ratio is almost 1:3 in favor of salary <=50K.  
# The model's ability to predict salary <=50K will be better than predicting salary >50K.

adult_df.groupby('salary').count()
